 Perfect — now you have the missing piece 🎯
With DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP, you can now:

identify which specialty codes are specialist
identify which are PCP
join that to provider
then join to claims/procedure data
then find the visit CPT/HCPCS codes used by specialists
That is the right way to find specialist visit codes from your database.
What each table now does
1) CASENET.PROVIDER
Provider master
Key columns:

PROVIDER_ID
PROVIDER_NAME
NPI
PROVIDER_TYPE
2) DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY
Maps provider to specialty code
Key columns:

PROVIDER_ID
PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
ACTIVE_FLAG
3) DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP
Translates specialty code to description
Key columns:

PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC
PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
ACTIVE_FLAG
So now you can tell whether a provider specialty code means:
Cardiology
Dermatology
Family Practice
Internal Medicine
etc.
Important idea
You are not directly finding “specialist CPT codes” from the lookup table.
Instead you are finding:

CPT/HCPCS codes that appear on claims for specialist providers
So the logic is:
Visit CPT/HCPCS code
+ provider belongs to specialist specialty
= specialist visit code candidate
Step 1: See all specialist specialties
Start here:
SELECT DISTINCT
    PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP
WHERE ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
ORDER BY PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC;
This tells you what specialty codes exist and what they mean.
Step 2: Separate PCP vs Specialist
Run this to inspect the descriptions:
SELECT DISTINCT
    PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP
WHERE ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
ORDER BY 2;
Look for PCP-like descriptions such as:
Family Practice
Internal Medicine
General Practice
Family Medicine
Pediatrics, if your business includes it as PCP
Geriatrics, depending on business definition
And specialist-like descriptions such as:
Cardiology
Dermatology
Neurology
Orthopedic Surgery
Endocrinology
Gastroenterology
Step 3: Build provider-to-specialty mapping
This gives you each provider with specialty description:
SELECT
    s.PROVIDER_ID,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE,
    s.ACTIVE_FLAG
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1;
Step 4: Join provider table too
Since CASENET.PROVIDER.PROVIDER_ID is string and specialty table provider_id is numeric, use cast:
SELECT
    p.PROVIDER_ID,
    p.PROVIDER_NAME,
    p.NPI,
    p.PROVIDER_TYPE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1;
Now you have the provider and its specialty description.
Step 5: Define specialists
Now decide which providers count as specialists.
Option A: Use PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
If PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE already clearly says values like:
PCP
SPECIALIST
then great — use it directly.
Check first:

SELECT DISTINCT PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP
ORDER BY 1;
If that column is reliable, your filter becomes:
AND l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE = 'SPECIALIST'
Option B: Use specialty description
If type is not reliable, use description and exclude PCP descriptions:
AND UPPER(l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC) NOT IN (
    'FAMILY PRACTICE',
    'INTERNAL MEDICINE',
    'GENERAL PRACTICE',
    'FAMILY MEDICINE'
)
Step 6: Now find the visit CPT/HCPCS codes used by specialists
This is the key step.
You need your claim procedure table here, probably something like:

FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE
or another claims procedure table
Then join:
claim/procedure
provider
provider specialty
specialty lookup
and pull distinct procedure codes.
Main pattern
SELECT DISTINCT
    cp.PROCEDURE_CODE,
    pc.PROCEDURE_NAME,
    pc.PROCEDURE_DESCRIPTION
FROM YOUR_CLAIM_PROCEDURE_TABLE cp
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER p
    ON cp.PROVIDER_ID = p.PROVIDER_ID
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROCEDURECODE pc
    ON cp.PROCEDURE_CODE = pc.PROCEDURE_CODE
WHERE s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE = 'SPECIALIST';
This gives you all procedure codes billed by specialists.
Step 7: Narrow to visit-type codes only
Not every code billed by a specialist is a visit.
Many will be:
lab
imaging
injections
surgery
procedures
So filter to office/outpatient evaluation and management visit codes.
Good starting filter:
99202–99205
99211–99215
maybe hospital/outpatient visit-related HCPCS like G0463
Example:
SELECT DISTINCT
    cp.PROCEDURE_CODE,
    pc.PROCEDURE_NAME,
    pc.PROCEDURE_DESCRIPTION
FROM YOUR_CLAIM_PROCEDURE_TABLE cp
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER p
    ON cp.PROVIDER_ID = p.PROVIDER_ID
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROCEDURECODE pc
    ON cp.PROCEDURE_CODE = pc.PROCEDURE_CODE
WHERE s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE = 'SPECIALIST'
  AND (
        cp.PROCEDURE_CODE BETWEEN '99202' AND '99215'
        OR cp.PROCEDURE_CODE = 'G0463'
      );
That gives you likely specialist visit codes.
Step 8: Best discovery approach from your database
If your goal is to discover what specialist visit codes are actually used in your environment, do this:
SELECT
    cp.PROCEDURE_CODE,
    pc.PROCEDURE_NAME,
    pc.PROCEDURE_DESCRIPTION,
    COUNT(*) AS CLAIM_COUNT
FROM YOUR_CLAIM_PROCEDURE_TABLE cp
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER p
    ON cp.PROVIDER_ID = p.PROVIDER_ID
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROCEDURECODE pc
    ON cp.PROCEDURE_CODE = pc.PROCEDURE_CODE
WHERE s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE = 'SPECIALIST'
GROUP BY
    cp.PROCEDURE_CODE,
    pc.PROCEDURE_NAME,
    pc.PROCEDURE_DESCRIPTION
ORDER BY CLAIM_COUNT DESC;
Then inspect the top codes and keep only true visit/E&M codes.
This is often the best real-world way.

If PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE is not clean
Use specialty description instead:
AND UPPER(l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC) NOT IN (
    'FAMILY PRACTICE',
    'INTERNAL MEDICINE',
    'GENERAL PRACTICE',
    'FAMILY MEDICINE'
)
or use positive inclusion:
AND UPPER(l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC) IN (
    'CARDIOLOGY',
    'DERMATOLOGY',
    'ENDOCRINOLOGY',
    'GASTROENTEROLOGY',
    'NEUROLOGY',
    'ORTHOPEDIC SURGERY'
)
Positive inclusion is often safer when you are validating.
